and so forth. The introduction is a general survey in English of Cambodian literature, and each section has an introduction in Cambodian. For pedagogical reasons, the selections are presented roughly in reverse chronological order, from modern prose to the very esoteric and somewhat archaic verse of the Ream-Kie (the Cambodian version of the Ramayana). The reader concludes with a bibliography of some sixty items on Cambodian literature.The glossary combines the 4,000 or so items introduced in this reader with the more than 6,000 introduced in the previous two readers, making it the largest Cambodian-English glossary compiled to date. The definitions are more general and complete than one usually finds in a simple reader glossary, in which definitions are normally context-specific. Because the glossary is so useful in itself, it is being made available separately as well as bound with the reader.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aKhmer languagevReaders. 4aAsian Studies. 4aLanguage Arts & Linguistics. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aFOREIGN LANGUAGE STUDY / Southeast Asian Languages (see also Vietnamese).2bisacsh1 aHuffman, Franklin E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aProum, Im, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Archive (pre 2000) eBook Packagez978311064968008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172179340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501721793423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501721793/original  a978-3-11-053617-1  Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000b2000  a978-3-11-064968-0  Asian Studies Archive (pre 2000) eBook Packageb2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LS  